---
import ExampleCard from "../ExampleCard.astro";
import JsonExampleCard from "../JsonExampleCard.astro";

const agentReadyJson = JSON.stringify(
  {
    event: "dependency.resolve.failed",
    package: "std",
    source: "packages/app/riot.toml",
    wanted: "std",
    found: null,
    fix: "riot add std",
  },
  null,
  2,
);
---

<section class="jr-section" id="voice">
  <div class="jr-section-body">
    <div class="jr-intro">
      <h2>Voice & Writing</h2>
      <p>
        How Riot sounds across all surfaces: from the CLI to the web.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="guideline-prose voice-opening">
      <p>
        Riot’s Jolly Roger has a distinct sound: direct, opinionated, helpful,
        and joyful. We speak our mind out loud, respectfully and candidly.
      </p>
      <p>
        Our users are smart, and we acknowledge that, but they also have a job
        to do. Detours for the sake of it are not worth their time. We do not
        expect them to know everything or keep every detail fresh in mind.
      </p>
      <p>
        When designing interfaces for the Riot ecosystem, use this voice as a
        practical tool. It should make documentation easier to scan, CLI output
        easier to trust, error messages easier to recover from, and product
        surfaces easier to act on.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="guideline-rows">
      <article class="guideline-row">
        <div class="voice-quality-list">
          <section class="voice-quality">
            <div class="guideline-prose">
              <h4 class="voice-quality__title">Be Direct</h4>
              <p>
                Just say the thing. Riot copy should be clear of fluff. We
                would rather make a sentence obviously wrong than make it hard
                to see whether it is wrong.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="guideline-example-set">
              <ExampleCard label="Bad" tone="bad">You may want to consider checking whether dependency resolution encountered an issue.</ExampleCard>
              <ExampleCard label="Good" tone="good">Riot could not resolve std.

Run riot add std.</ExampleCard>
            </div>
          </section>

          <section class="voice-quality">
            <div class="guideline-prose">
              <h4 class="voice-quality__title">Be Opinionated</h4>
              <p>
                Do not be afraid to state the preferred path or the preferred
                way of doing something. It might not be exactly what every user
                wants, and that is okay. Do not try to offer solutions for
                everyone all of the time.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="guideline-example-set">
              <ExampleCard label="Bad" tone="bad">Riot supports many project layouts depending on your preference.</ExampleCard>
              <ExampleCard label="Good" tone="good">Put packages in packages/.

Riot looks there first, and every generated command assumes that layout.</ExampleCard>
            </div>
          </section>

          <section class="voice-quality">
            <div class="guideline-prose">
              <h4 class="voice-quality__title">Be Helpful</h4>
              <p>
                Always provide contextual help and next steps to unblock
                developers. Remember, they are not here to marvel at the tool;
                they are here to ship. Help them ship.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="guideline-example-set">
              <ExampleCard label="Bad" tone="bad">Build failed.</ExampleCard>
              <ExampleCard label="Good" tone="good">Build failed in packages/std.

Run riot test std --failed, or open the diagnostic above for the exact file and fix.</ExampleCard>
            </div>
          </section>

          <section class="voice-quality">
            <div class="guideline-prose">
              <h4 class="voice-quality__title">Be Joyful</h4>
              <p>
                Feel empowered to be bold and laugh, then relentlessly fix
                everything that removes joy: friction, slowness, bugginess,
                vague feedback, and dead ends.
              </p>
            </div>
            <div class="guideline-example-set">
              <ExampleCard label="Bad" tone="bad">Operation completed successfully.</ExampleCard>
              <ExampleCard label="Good" tone="good">Formatted 128 files.

Nothing else to fix.</ExampleCard>
            </div>
          </section>
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="guideline-row" id="voice-agent-ready">
        <h3>Agent-ready</h3>
        <div class="guideline-prose">
          <p>
            Being agent-friendly means that everything we build must have a
            clear, structured way of being used by an agent rather than a
            human. That may be an <code>llms.txt</code> file, uniform <code>--json</code>
            flags, stable anchors, predictable labels, or machine-readable
            output.
          </p>
          <p>
            Do not hide the messy details of data or errors, but remember that
            agents do not think the way you expect them to. A little context
            engineering can go a long way.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="guideline-example-set">
          <ExampleCard label="Bad" tone="bad">Something went wrong while resolving dependencies.</ExampleCard>
          <ExampleCard label="Good text" tone="good">package: std
source:  packages/app/riot.toml
wanted:  std
found:   no matching dependency
fix:     riot add std</ExampleCard>
          <JsonExampleCard label="Better JSON" code={agentReadyJson} />
        </div>
      </article>

      <article class="guideline-row" id="voice-coding">
        <h3>Coding voice</h3>
        <div class="guideline-prose">
          <p>
            Perhaps a surprising aspect of the Jolly Roger is that it applies
            to how we write code too. The same voice becomes code that is
            understandable, malleable, correct, and fast, in that order.
          </p>
          <div class="coding-values">
            <section class="coding-value">
              <h4 class="voice-quality__title">Understandability</h4>
              <p>
                Code is read more than it is written, so it must be structured,
                documented, named, and designed to be understandable. There are
                many ways to achieve correctness, refactorability, and
                performance, but we should be willing to balance them to keep
                code understandable. If we cannot understand it, it does not
                matter how fast, correct, or modular it is.
              </p>
            </section>
            <section class="coding-value">
              <h4 class="voice-quality__title">Malleability</h4>
              <p>
                Code should be built to change. In today’s agentic development
                world, making code easier to evolve also makes correctness and
                performance easier to improve.
              </p>
            </section>
            <section class="coding-value">
              <h4 class="voice-quality__title">Correctness</h4>
              <p>
                Code should be built to be correct, even at the expense of
                performance. We use the tools at our disposal: unit tests,
                properties, fuzzing, sanitizers, and clear contracts.
              </p>
            </section>
            <section class="coding-value">
              <h4 class="voice-quality__title">Performance</h4>
              <p>
                Code should be fast, and it should be aware of its performance
                model and cost.
              </p>
            </section>
          </div>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
